   <item>
    <widget class="QTextBrowser" name="textBrowser">
     <property name="html">
      <string>&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;
&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;meta name=&quot;qrichtext&quot; content=&quot;1&quot; /&gt;&lt;meta charset=&quot;utf-8&quot; /&gt;&lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;
p, li { white-space: pre-wrap; }
hr { height: 1px; border-width: 0; }
li.unchecked::marker { content: &quot;\2610&quot;; }
li.checked::marker { content: &quot;\2612&quot;; }
&lt;/style&gt;&lt;/head&gt;&lt;body style=&quot; font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:9pt; font-weight:400; font-style:normal;&quot;&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size:12pt;&quot;&gt;This Tab performs INS simulations based on provided DFT results, either from the included DFT database or the user's own DFT calculations. The DFT database contains 11,429 entries, including 10,023 from phonondb (see Ref. [4]) and 1,406 from the current authors (unpublished). Data files required (POSCAR-unitcell, FORCE_SETS or FORCE_CONSTANTS, mesh.conf, and in some cases BORN) as input for INS calculations are already available. You may also choose to use your own DFT calculation results, in which case check &amp;quot;Use My DFT Data&amp;quot; and specify the folder containing the above files.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;-qt-paragraph-type:empty; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; font-size:12pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size:12pt;&quot;&gt;When using the provided database, you may search the entries in various ways (selected from the &amp;quot;Type&amp;quot; dropdown list). The search &amp;quot;Value&amp;quot; may contain wildcards (as a valid regex). Once you find the crystal, click on it to choose.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;-qt-paragraph-type:empty; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; font-size:12pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size:12pt;&quot;&gt;Step 2 is optional, but it is often convenient to check the phonon dispersion and DOS before the INS simulation. In some cases, negative frequencies (imaginary modes) exist, which could indicate insufficient modeling or actual instability of the structure. It is essential to be aware of this situation when interpreting the results.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;-qt-paragraph-type:empty; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; font-size:12pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size:12pt;&quot;&gt;Step 3: Set up INS simulation (Phonopy and OCLIMAX). This step generates a *.params file in the working directory. Detailed instructions can be found in the popup window (the help button within).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;-qt-paragraph-type:empty; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; font-size:12pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size:12pt;&quot;&gt;Step 4: Run INS simulation. Depending on the size/complexity of the calculation, the time needed to complete this step can vary significantly. Monitor the terminal output for progress. Generally speaking, the run time is determined by the size of the mesh.yaml in the working directory, as well as the requested quality of the calculation (number of  E and Q bins). As a rule of thumb, the size of the mesh.yaml file should be smaller than 1GB (in most cases on the order of 10~100MB), the number of E bins should be less than a few thousand for 1D spectra, and the number of E and Q bins should be less than a few hundred each for 2D spectra. When in doubt, it is recommended to start from a relatively coarse calculation and then gradually increase the quality to achieve convergence without making the run time unacceptably long.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;-qt-paragraph-type:empty; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; font-size:12pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size:12pt;&quot;&gt;Step 5: Plot the resulting spectra. For 2D spectra, you may make an interactive cross-section plot where 1D cuts along X and Y will be displayed following the cursor. You may open multiple plots simultaneously. Data files will have a time stamp in their names so they are not overwritten.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/body&gt;&lt;/html&gt;</string>
     </property>
    </widget>
   </item>
